3 Data

data(Wage)
Wage <- subset(Wage, select = -c(logwage)) # remove y var
colnames(Wage)
##  [1] "year"       "age"        "maritl"     "race"       "education" 
##  [6] "region"     "jobclass"   "health"     "health_ins" "wage"
dim(Wage)
## [1] 3000   10

4 Train and test sets

inTrain <- createDataPartition(y=Wage$wage, p=0.7, list=FALSE)
training <- Wage[inTrain,]
testing <- Wage[-inTrain,]
dim(training)[1]+dim(testing)[1]
## [1] 3000

5 Feature Plot

featurePlot(x=training[,c("age","education","jobclass")],y=training$wage, plot="pairs")

# Individual plots

qplot(age, wage, data=training,colour=education)

# Fit a linear model

#training$education <- as.factor(training$education)



modFit <- train(wage ~ age + jobclass + education,
                method="lm",
                data=training)
finMod <- modFit$finalModel
print(modFit)
## Linear Regression 
## 
## 2102 samples
##    3 predictor
## 
## No pre-processing
## Resampling: Bootstrapped (25 reps) 
## Summary of sample sizes: 2102, 2102, 2102, 2102, 2102, 2102, ...

6 Diagnostics

plot(finMod,pch=19,cex=0.5)

qplot(finMod$fitted.values,finMod$residuals,data=training,colour=race)

7 Plot against index of dataset

plot(finMod$residuals,pch=19)

# Post mortmen on your analysis

pred <- predict(modFit, testing)
qplot(wage, pred, colour=year,data=testing)
